547","1556":"1556","1587":"1587","1586":"1586","1585":"1585","aft 1547 ":"na 1547","October 1592":"oktober 1592","January 1547":"januari 1547","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"January 1547–October 1592":"January 1547–October 1592","1547–1592":"1547–1592","1556–1586":"1556–1586","1586–1624":"1586–1624","1515–1547":"1515–1547","1515–Female":"1515–Deceased","Aft 1586":"after 1586","1571":"1571","1592":"1592","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1624":"1624","1547":"1547","1556":"1556","1587":"1587","1586":"1586","1585":"1585","aft 1547 ":"after 1547","October 1592":"October 1592","January 1547":"January 1547","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a stone-built wall, e.g. one used to fortify a town or to keep back the encroachment of the sea (Middle English <i>wall</i> ‘wall’, Old English <i>wall</i>, <i>weall</i>, from Latin <i>vallum</i> ‘rampart, palisade’), or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Wall (Staffordshire).","English (West Midlands): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, northern Middle English <i>wall(e)</i> (Old English (Mercian) <i>wæll(a)</i>; compare   Well  ).","Irish (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of <i>de Valle</i> (Gaelicized form <i>de Bhál</i>), the name of a Norman family established in Munster and Connacht."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallander","meanings":["Swedish: variant of   Wall  , with the addition of the suffix <i>-ander</i>, derived from Greek <i>anēr</i> (genitive <i>andros</i>) ‘man’."]},{"name":"Wallenberg","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental name composed of the elements   Wall   + the plural suffix <i>- en</i> (originally German) + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","History: While working as a businessman in Budapest in 1944, Raoul Wallenberg (1912–?47) was entrusted by the Swedish government with the protection of Hungarian Jews from the Nazis. Wallenberg helped about 95,000 Jews to escape death by issuing them Swedish passports. When Soviet forces took control of Budapest in 1945, he was arrested, taken to Moscow, and imprisoned. The Soviet authorities stated that he died in prison in 1947."]},{"name":"Well","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>well(e)</i> ‘spring, stream, well’ (Old English <i>well(a)</i>).","German: from a short form of the personal names <i>Wallo</i>, <i>Walilo</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wël</i> ‘round’."]},{"name":"Walle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Arnulfo, Efrain, Emilia, Evodio, Frederico, Jaime, Javier, Jesus, Jose, Juan, Justo.","English and German: variant of   Wall  . This surname is also found in Mexico.","Norwegian: variant of   Valle  ."]},{"name":"Wallen","meanings":["Swedish (mainly <b>Wallén</b>): topographic or ornamental name composed of a variant of the element <i>vall</i> ‘grassy bank, pasture’ (see   Wall  ) or the root of Latin <i>vallis</i> ‘valley’ (representing Swedish <i>dal</i>) + the adjectival suffix <i>-én/-en</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Wallin   and   Walen  ."]},{"name":"Walls","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Wall  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (Derry): in Ireland this name is also sometimes a variant of   Walsh  ."]}]},{"name":"Lewis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form, since the Middle Ages, of the French name   Louis .  In modern use it is also in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this given name, or from Anglicized forms of Gaelic <i>Mac Lughaidh</i> ‘son of  <b>Lughaidh</b> ’  or Welsh Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewys","meanings":["form, since the Middle Ages, of the French name   Louis .  In modern use it is also in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this given name, or from Anglicized forms of Gaelic <i>Mac Lughaidh</i> ‘son of  <b>Lughaidh</b> ’  or Welsh Llewelyn ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":2,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":11,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":22,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":24,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of Engli